Then create a subtask.  You'll get this log output:
{noformat}
[DebugListener]: DebugListener.issueCreated
[DebugListener]: Issue: [#10203] stuff 123
[DebugListener]: Comment: null
[DebugListener]: Change Group: null
[DebugListener]: Parent id: 10100
[DebugListener]: Event Type: Issue Created
[DebugListener]:  Time: Sat Jul 14 01:25:14 EST 2012

[DebugListener]: DebugListener.issueUpdated
[DebugListener]: 	labels changed from '' to 'test'
[DebugListener]: Issue: [#10203] stuff 123
[DebugListener]: Comment: null
[DebugListener]: Change Group: [GenericEntity:ChangeGroup][id,10101][author,admin][created,2012-07-14 01:28:21.066][issue,10203]
[DebugListener]: Parent id: null
[DebugListener]: Event Type: Issue Updated
[DebugListener]:  Time: Sat Jul 14 01:28:21 EST 2012
{noformat}

The problem is exactly as they described:
* We first create the subtask (via issue service) in createIssue() in CreateIssueDetails.doExecute()
* The issueCreated event triggers (by the issueService)
* The DebugListener then kicks in and runs code in the issueCreated() method. Here the issue object *has* a parentId set (because it was probably explicitly set by the webwork action or issue service)
* It then triggers an update of this issue by adding a label. At some stage during this process we must lookup the issue again by ID and then dispatch the issue updated event.  Now we haven't run the doPostCreationTask() method yet which establishes the parent/child link in the DB.  The IssueImpl looks up the parentId via this parent/child link however and so now that we've looked up the issue via DB but we don't have the link yet the parentId comes back as null.   
* Finally the doPostCreationTask() method runs in CreateSubTaskIssueDetails which establishes the parent/child issue link.  *now* if we retrieved the issue again from the db it would have a parent ID set but at this stage it's too late.

{quote}

We will need this to be fixed, as GreenHopper (amongst others) definitely makes use of listeners to synchronise Version and Component hierarchy, and this prevents 3rd party developers from using this feature in combination with the own listeners that want to work with subtasks and their parents.

Having said that though, it's not urgent as the workaround would be to not run two separate listeners like this (not run a hierarchy in GH, and disable those listeners).

